Collector Guy wrote, _"Law enforcement scanning every message from innocent people is only going to cause distrust, and for good reason."_

True. I would add that a concern over 'causing distrust' is maybe too little of a consideration in the bigger picture. In the bigger picture, I think it makes sense to consider whether 'public distrust' matters at all. Two lines of thought here:

1. Psychology and sociology suggest that people -- _individually and collectively_ -- tend not to respond en masse to simply violations of ethics. This is generally true, but it's especially true when the violation doesn't confront them directly. A data breach to most non-tech people is just a factoid. It's almost guaranteed that non-techies don't pay attention to such things, and the ones who do end up hearing about it probably don't go out changing passwords right away. To them, it's too abstract and, in their opinion, not particularly relevant to their concerns.

The heuristic seems to be something like, _"If I can get up tomorrow and mostly do what I expected to do, then nothing else matters."_

2. History suggests that even when people do begin to take notice of an issue, there's often such a polarized view about that matter that rather than people uniting ini solidarity against the power, instution, government, etc., that's responsible for that issue... the people just end up bickering amongst themselves. It's the ages-old tactic of 'divide and rule', and it's ages-old for a reason: it's proven tot be both reliable and effective.

All that said, I think it's more useful (for those of us who are actually paying attention) to recognize the illegitimacy of existing power structures. I think it was one of the Rothschilds who said, _"Give me control of a nation's currency and I care not who makes its laws."_ That's a relevant insight to how power operates. So, if we who are paying attention are serious about safeguarding our liberty, privacy, etc., then it seems to me we need to go further back in the 'chain of events' to address the root-cause of such problems. Because unless we do that, the endless stream of 'current events' that catch our attention only serve to distract us from going back to the *ROOT* cause of society's ills.

I think this characterization is correct. As to whether it's likely that the masses will every grow out of their obsession with -polarized bickering', I doubt that they will. And the conclusions we may draw from this premise are as disappointing as they are disheartening because, if I'm thinking about it correctly, then it seems inevitable that the ills of society will continue either until power succeeds in a full-scale tyranny, or until the society collapses under the weight of its own agenda to own and control everything and everyone.

I suppose time will tell whether what I'm thinking is correct, and whether things will unfold as I suspect. This is one case where I hope I'm wrong but... right now, I don't think that's likely to be true.
